# Solvers

Basin ships a growing catalogue of solvers, all driven by the same `Executor`
loop. Pick one based on what your problem provides (a gradient? only costs?
residuals?) and whether it is constrained.

## First-order

- **`GradientDescent`** — steepest descent with a pluggable step rule:
  `Constant`, `Backtracking`, `MoreThuente`, or `Wolfe` line searches.
- **`ProjectedGradientDescent`** — gradient descent for box-constrained
  problems, projecting each step back onto the feasible box.

## Derivative-free

- **`NelderMead`** — the classic reflection / expansion / contraction simplex;
  needs only a `CostFunction`. `NelderMead::adaptive()` uses the
  dimension-aware coefficients of Gao & Han (2012).
- **`Brent`** — robust 1-D minimization on a bracketed interval; also used
  inside line searches.

## Quasi-Newton

- **`BFGS`** — dense quasi-Newton with a full approximate Hessian.
- **`LBFGS`** — limited-memory BFGS (two-loop recursion) for larger problems.
- **`LBFGSB`** — L-BFGS with box bounds, a faithful port of Nocedal's
  Fortran v3.0.

## Nonlinear least squares

For problems expressed as residuals (`Residual` + `Jacobian`):

- **`GaussNewton`** — undamped normal-equations solver.
- **`LevenbergMarquardt`** — damped least squares with Nielsen's (1999) update
  rule; the workhorse for curve fitting.
- **`Trf`** — trust-region reflective: Levenberg–Marquardt with box bounds.

## Global & stochastic

- **`CmaEs`** / **`BoundedCmaEs`** — covariance-matrix adaptation evolution
  strategy (Hansen, 2016), unconstrained and box-bounded.
- **`RandomSearch`** — elitist (1+λ) uniform sampling over a box.
- **`Ssga`** — steady-state genetic algorithm (BLX-α crossover, replace-worst).

## Memetic (composed)

These run a local solver inside a global one — an example of Basin's solver
composition primitives:

- **`CmaInject`** / **`BoundedCmaInject`** — CMA-ES with per-generation local
  polishing of the best individuals.
- **`MaLsChCma`** — a memetic algorithm with persistent local-search chains.

## Constrained (composed)

These wrap any gradient inner solver in an outer loop that handles linear
constraints:

- **`BarrierMethod`** — log-barrier interior-point continuation for linear
  inequality constraints (`A x ≤ b`); needs a strictly feasible start.
- **`AugmentedLagrangianMethod`** — quadratic penalty plus multiplier updates
  for linear equality constraints (`A x = b`); tolerates an infeasible start.

## Backends and constraints

Two design rules shape which solver you can use where:

- **Constraints are first-class and type-checked.** Box bounds live on the
  *problem* (`BoxConstraints`). Handing a constrained problem to an
  unconstrained solver is a compile error, not a runtime surprise.
- **Backends are tiered.** First-order and derivative-free solvers stay generic
  over the parameter type (`Vec<f64>`, nalgebra, ndarray, faer). Linear-algebra
  heavy solvers (the quasi-Newton and least-squares families) require a backend
  that implements the richer math they need — so an unsupported parameter type
  fails to compile rather than at runtime.

The matrix below summarizes support: ✓ means it compiles and runs on that
parameter type, ✗ means it is a compile-time error (the tiering rule above).

| Solver | Family | `Vec<f64>` | nalgebra | ndarray | faer |
| --- | --- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| `GradientDescent` | First-order | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `ProjectedGradientDescent` | First-order | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `NelderMead` | Derivative-free | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `Brent` | Derivative-free | — | — | — | — |
| `BFGS` | Quasi-Newton | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✗ |
| `LBFGS` | Quasi-Newton | ✓ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `LBFGSB` | Quasi-Newton | ✓ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `GaussNewton` | Least squares | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `LevenbergMarquardt` | Least squares | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `Trf` | Least squares | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `CmaEs` | Global | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `BoundedCmaEs` | Global | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `RandomSearch` | Global | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `Ssga` | Global | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `CmaInject` | Memetic | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `BoundedCmaInject` | Memetic | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `MaLsChCma` | Memetic | ✗ | ✓ | ✗ | ✓ |
| `BarrierMethod` | Constrained | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `AugmentedLagrangianMethod` | Constrained | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |

`Brent` minimizes over a scalar `f64` interval (1-D), so the vector-backend
choice does not apply.

Each solver's page on [docs.rs](https://docs.rs/basin) carries a **Backends**
note listing exactly which parameter types it supports.

See [getting started](../getting-started/) for a worked example, or open the
[visualizer](../../visualizer/) to watch several of these solvers converge.
